                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.5048/313: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reber</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 1, 1930—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>86. Your telegrams No. 133, September 30, 11 p.m., and No. 134, September 30,
                    midnight. You will please comment on the substance <pb facs="0450" n="356"
                        xml:id="pg_356"/> of the President’s proposed program and advise as to what
                    part of these measures could actually be put into effect by executive order, or
                    otherwise, as an immediate earnest of the Liberian Government’s intention to
                    proceed with real reform. Do you have any suggestions regarding the nature of
                    the reply by this Government to President King?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
